Each of the seven or so silks secreted by orb-web-building spiders is incorporated into their webs, and each has distinct properties (
 Blamires 
  et al., 2017b
 ). The most impressive of which are those of major ampullate (MA) silk. The role of this silk is to intercept insects, or on occasions, birds or bats (
 Nentwig and Heimer, 1987; Nyffeler and Knornschild, 2012), in full flight by absorbing and dissipating the exorbitant amounts of kinetic energy imparted into the web (
 Craig, 1987; 
 Sensenig 
  et al., 2012
 , 
 2013; 
 Harmer 
  et al., 2015
 ).
